✅ Set A: Docker Image and Container Lifecycle
A. Pull Ubuntu 20.04 image

Command:

docker pull ubuntu:20.04

Description:
Downloads the Ubuntu image with version 20.04 from Docker Hub to your local system.

B. List all available images

Command:

docker images

Description:
Displays all Docker images stored locally, including repository, tag, image ID, and size.

C. Pull Ubuntu latest image

Command:

docker pull ubuntu:latest

Description:
Downloads the latest version of the Ubuntu image.

D. Remove Ubuntu 20.04 image

Command:

docker rmi ubuntu:20.04

Description:
Deletes the Ubuntu 20.04 image from your local system to free space.

E. Run container (ubuntu-os) in detached + interactive mode

Command:

docker run -dit --name ubuntu-os ubuntu:latest

Description:
Creates and runs a container named ubuntu-os in detached mode with interactive terminal enabled.

F. Stop the container

Command:

docker stop ubuntu-os

Description:
Stops the running container.

G. Restart the container

Command:

docker restart ubuntu-os

Description:
Restarts the stopped container.

H. List all containers

Command:

docker ps -a

Description:
Shows all containers (running + stopped).

I. Create directory inside container

Command:

docker exec ubuntu-os mkdir /myfolder

Description:
Creates a directory named myfolder inside the running container.

J. Verify directory

Command:

docker exec ubuntu-os ls /

Description:
Lists root directory contents to check if myfolder exists.

K. Stop container again

Command:

docker stop ubuntu-os

Description:
Stops the container safely.

L. Prune all containers

Command:

docker container prune

Description:
Deletes all stopped containers to free resources.

✅ Set B: PostgreSQL Containerization
A. Pull PostgreSQL image

Command:

docker pull postgres:latest

Description:
Downloads the latest PostgreSQL image.

B. Run PostgreSQL container

Command:

docker run -dit --name postgres-user1 -e POSTGRES_PASSWORD=admin postgres

Description:
Starts a PostgreSQL container with password admin in detached mode.

C. Connect to PostgreSQL CLI

Command:

docker exec -it postgres-user1 psql -U postgres

Description:
Opens PostgreSQL command line inside the container.

D. Create database

Command:

CREATE DATABASE mydb;

Description:
Creates a new database named mydb inside PostgreSQL.

E. Stop PostgreSQL container

Command:

docker stop postgres-user1

Description:
Stops the database container.

F. Delete container

Command:

docker rm postgres-user1

Description:
Removes the container permanently.

✅ Set C: Custom Image + Dockerfile
3) Dockerfile for Node.js App

Create a file named Dockerfile:

FROM node:18

WORKDIR /app

COPY . .

RUN npm install

EXPOSE 3000

CMD ["node", "app.js"]

Description:
Defines a Node.js environment, installs dependencies, and runs the app.

Build Image
docker build -t my-node-app .
Run Container
docker run -dit -p 3000:3000 my-node-app
✅ 4) Push Image to Docker Hub
A. Tag Image
docker tag my-node-app username/my-node-app
B. Login to Docker Hub
docker login
C. Push Image
docker push username/my-node-app

